steps.description:
You need to be cautious of woodworms and termites if you are bringing second hand furniture into your home. Look out for little holes and piles of frass (termite excrement). Fumigation works best to get rid of them, or use a DIY chemical treatment, and seal up any holes. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/ec/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/ec/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

If you leave the bugs in the wood, they will eat your art and possibly spread throughout your house. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b3/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-3Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-3Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b3/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-3Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-3Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Probably the simplest way to bring color into your garden is to take an old window frame and glue colored glass beads to it. You should use glue such as E6000, which dries clear. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/22/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/22/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

This can be displayed by standing it upright in a bed so that the sunlight comes through it. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/ca/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/ca/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Try anchoring it into the ground by attaching wooden stakes to the lower sides that can be driven at least 2 feet (0.6 m) into the ground for stability. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/22/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-4Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-4Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/22/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-4Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-4Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Silver or blue-tinted beads work well for giving the effect of bubbles. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/16/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-4Bullet4.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-4Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/16/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-4Bullet4.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-4Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

It can be fun to paint your own works of art onto blank windows. Not all glass paint will survive out of doors and some will peel, so choose your paint carefully. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/b\/be\/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-6Bullet1.jpg\/v4-460px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-6Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/b\/be\/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-6Bullet1.jpg\/v4-760px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-6Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

You may find it helps to wipe down the glass surface using alcohol before you paint. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/1\/17\/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-6Bullet2.jpg\/v4-460px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-6Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/1\/17\/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-6Bullet2.jpg\/v4-760px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-6Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Paints such as the Martha Stewart Glass range are said to be outdoor resistant. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/1\/16\/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-6Bullet3.jpg\/v4-460px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-6Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/1\/16\/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-6Bullet3.jpg\/v4-760px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-6Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Also try sealing using Polycrylic for added protection. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/c\/ce\/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-6Bullet4.jpg\/v4-460px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-6Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/c\/ce\/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-6Bullet4.jpg\/v4-760px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-6Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

As some paints need to be baked in the oven to seal the paints, you can either try removing the glass pane from the window to do so, or alternately paint a separate bit of glass and simply glue this onto your old window pane.

Creating a mini greenhouse can be a great place to store plants in a colorful way. You’ll need 6 small window frames of the same size and shape for this. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/dc/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-7Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-7Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/dc/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-7Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-7Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Make them safe by removing protruding nails and resealing the windows where needed. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/3b/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-7Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-7Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/3b/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-7Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-7Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Using hinges or small wooden blocks, attach 4 of the smaller windows to each other at right angles. This forms the 4 sides of your mini greenhouse. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/46/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-7Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-7Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/46/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-7Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-7Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Then use hinges to add a peaked roof using the last 2 windows. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/ac/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-7Bullet4.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-7Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/ac/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-7Bullet4.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-7Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Put some plants inside to finish it off. Remember, it will get pretty hot inside so choose plants that like heat and keep them well watered. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/fc/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-7Bullet5.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-7Bullet5.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/fc/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-7Bullet5.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-7Bullet5.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Remember, you don’t need to have glass in the frames of your old windows to use them in the garden. In fact, empty panes will make a great place for birds to perch. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/ff/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-8Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-8Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/ff/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-8Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-8Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Try painting old window frames using distressed paint techniques. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/87/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-8Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-8Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/87/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-8Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-8Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Outdoor chalk paint also works well. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/0a/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-8Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-8Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/0a/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-8Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-8Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Hang these on chains on the edge of your porch, from a tree branch, or on a barn door. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/48/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-8Bullet4.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-8Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/48/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-8Bullet4.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-8Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

A collection of frames painted different colors works well. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b9/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-8Bullet5.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-8Bullet5.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b9/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-8Bullet5.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-8Bullet5.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

An old window can be hung on a fence to create the illusion of a real window. This works especially well if you replace the glass panes with mirror panels. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/7b/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-9Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-9Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/7b/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-9Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-9Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

It also helps create a sense of space in a small garden. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/93/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-9Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-9Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/93/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-9Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-9Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

You can make a nice effect if you use a window with shutters. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2f/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-9Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-9Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2f/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-9Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-9Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Try painting these in a color that complements your fence. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/55/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-9Bullet4.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-9Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/55/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-9Bullet4.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-9Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Try some paint distressing techniques to create an aged effect. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/9e/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-9Bullet5.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-9Bullet5.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/9e/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-9Bullet5.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-9Bullet5.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Since garden art lives outdoors, it’s best to protect it before leaving it out for extended periods of time. Remember that any wood in contact with soil will get wet and may start to rot. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/84/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-13Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-13Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/84/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-13Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-13Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

To preserve the life of your garden art, treat it with a wood preservative if it is in contact with the ground, or raise it on a pressure-treated wood block. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f5/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-13Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-13Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f5/Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-13Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Garden-Art-with-Old-Windows-Step-13Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}
